                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">xauxau</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;10/24/2003&nbsp;: 12:36:34 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">This gets back to the original intent of this swerve from the topic. The laws in cases such as this seem to err on the side of the mother instead of the side of the unborn child. I find that to be a VERY partisian situation. Liberals would never go for protecting unborn life, no matter how cruel. While the Religous right could never see a situation where abortion is justifiable. <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />You keep missing the point.<br /><br />The specific law that you object too has nothing to do with womens rights, abortion, partisan politics, liberals OR the Religious Right.  It was formulated centuries ago, in another country, in a pre-modern society, by legal scholars who had radically different ideas about religion, science, family life, personal rights and the purposes and scope of the criminal law than people commonly hold today.  Its actually the product of a mindset almost totally alien to ours.  That it happened to be the law of the state of Illinois at the end of the twentieth century is the result of a bizaare and peculiar set of historical facts.  But even so, it was clearly the law.  The appeals court had little choice but to apply the existing law to the case in front of it.<br /><br />And the facts in this case are weak for a murder case.  In the overwhelming majority of murder cases, the prosecutor has some evidence of what killed the victim before deciding what charges to bring against the perps.  In this case, the prosecutor was NEVER able to determine the actual cause of death.  That would have caused serious problems in ANY capital case, both with a jury and on appeal.  In this case, it was fatal, because the prosecutor had to prove, beyond a reasonable doubt, that the child had survived the birthing process.  Without an exact cause of death, he couldn't.<br /><br />Remember, prosecutors in other places HAVE obtained guilty pleas from parents accussed of murdering their children immediately after birth.  Other famous neonaticidal moms have done time in jail: Stephanie Warwick was convicted in 1993, Amy Grossberg plead guilty in 1996, and Melissa Drexler (the Prom Mom) plead guilty to mansluaghter in 1998.  These were all notorious cases in which the mother obtained top-rank legal defenses.  But in those cases, the prosector was able to prove the child had been born alive from the forensic results of the childrens' autopsies.<br /><br />And here's another little factoid for you.  Women in the USA are actually LESS likely to murder their children in their first week of life now than they were 30 years ago.  Both the absolute number and rate of such homicides has been steadily declining for decades.  But despite the fact that baby killing was once more common, until Warwick's conviction in 1993, no woman was successfully prosecuted for killing her own child during the first few days of life. And thats in any English-speaking, common law country, not just the USA.<br /><br />Thats because until about 10 years ago, nobody seems to have thought these women were criminals.  The assumption in most cases was that they must be seriously disturbed.  Prosecutors rarely brought charges, and juries refused to convict in those rare instances where charges where brought.  Echoes of these kinds of prejudices can be seen in public feeling about the Andrea Yates case.  <br /><br />Ultimately, this case doesn't signify anything about abortion or about how our society or legal system views the 'unborn'.  Its more about how educated society of 350 years ago viewed unborn children (which was pretty much as legal non-entities), and about how the job of appellate courts is to enforce the law as it actually is, even when juries, trial judges, prosecutors and even the appellate judges themselves wish it was different.<br /><br /></span></font></td>
              </tr>
