 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">xauxau</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;10/23/2003&nbsp;: 4:40:28 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">I tried to find what that law specifically states but since your the local ambulance chaser, maybe you can dig it up between saving the world from the evil right to life folks and working on protecting the civil rights of illegal immigrants.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Its no surprise you were not able to find a specific statute.  It doesn't exist.  The reporter didn't know what they were talking about.  Reporters for major national newspapers rarely understand the details of the stories they cover, let alone hacks working for the Catholic Citizens website.<br /><br />They are probably talking about Illinois' enabling act, which adopted Anglo-Saxon common law as the common law of the state.  Most states have statutes to that effect on their books, passed right after the state was admitted to the USA.  Legal scholars two centuries ago believed such laws were necessary because common law in England was a product of the King's soveriegnty.  And obviously, the King had no soveriegnty over the territory of a state in the USA.  So the state legislature had to 'enable' common law, which ultimately almost all did.<br /><br />But so what?<br /><br />Admittedly the law the judge was applying was beyond old.  It was ancient.  But the law doesn't change in its fundamentals just because it gets old, even if a noisy minority thinks it ought to be changed.  It changes because NEW laws are passed.<br /><br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">If I understand your higher level of thought,<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Thats not likely any time soon, but recognizing your own intellectual sloth and incoherence is the first step to curing it.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"> I think your saying that as long as nobody heard that baby cry we have to assume it wasn't.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />See?  You didn't understand.<br /><br />Thats not what I said at all.  I said there has to be SOME EVIDENCE the baby was alive at birth before an appellate court can uphold a conviction.  In fact, the standard for sending someone to prison BEYOND A REASONABLE DOUBT.  In the case you are talking about, there was ZERO evidence the child was alive.<br /><br />The State's star eyewitness admitted he had no idea. The State's medical examiner admitted the autopsy evidence was consistent with the child being stillborn, although she wrote otherwise adter the autopsy because the police had told her they had a witness to the child's murder.  The autopsy file was looked at by two defense experts (both qualified forensic patholigists, unlike the general practice physician the prosecutor called) who testified the child WAS DEFINITELY stillborn.<br /><br />And if the kid was stillborn, there was no murder.  Yeah, a responsible mother should have sought medical care when she went into labor.  But Illinois law didn't require her too. And we don't send people to prison, no matter how monstrous and evil, unless they actually break the law, AND THE PROSECUTOR CAN PROVE IT.  In this caes, the prosecutor presented no real evidence to support the charge: murder.<br /><br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Ahaha, your cute..<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />No. I'm not.  I've said it before:  I consider comparisons between myself and a rhinocerous to be insulting to the rhino.<br /><br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Yeah, so I look at the facts and come to the conclustion that she is a killer<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />HAH!  You didn't bother to look at the facts.  You never even read the appellate decision, let alone looked into the facts of the case.  You just read some anti-abortion literature that told you what to think, then thought it.<br /><br /><br /><br /></span></font></td>
